00:00:36.030 --> 00:00:45.230
The that I'd like to start with
today is average value.

00:00:45.230 --> 00:00:47.620
This is something that I
mentioned a little bit

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:50.290
earlier, and there was a
misprint on the board, so I

00:00:50.290 --> 00:00:54.980
want to make sure that we have
the definitions straight.

00:00:54.980 --> 00:00:56.770
And also the reasoning
straight.

00:00:56.770 --> 00:00:59.090
This is one of the most
important applications of

00:00:59.090 --> 00:01:03.840
integrals, one of the most
important examples.

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:08.300
If you take the average
of a bunch of numbers,

00:01:08.300 --> 00:01:10.420
that looks like this.

00:01:10.420 --> 00:01:15.500
And we can view this as
sampling a function.

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:17.570
As we would with
Riemann's sum.

00:01:17.570 --> 00:01:25.070
And what I said last week was
that this tends to this

00:01:25.070 --> 00:01:32.960
expression here, which is called
the continuous average.

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:43.550
So this guy is the continuous
average.

00:01:43.550 --> 00:01:49.270
Or just the average of f.

00:01:49.270 --> 00:01:53.490
And I want to explain that, just
to make sure that we're

00:01:53.490 --> 00:01:56.380
all on the same page.

00:01:56.380 --> 00:01:59.530
In general, if you have a
function and you want to

00:01:59.530 --> 00:02:03.770
interpret the integral, our
first interpretation was that

00:02:03.770 --> 00:02:09.860
it's something like the
area under the curve.

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:15.440
But average value is another
reasonable interpretation.

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:20.450
Namely, if you take equally
spaced points here, starting

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:28.520
with x0, x1, x2, all the way
up to xn, which is the left

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:34.320
point b, and then we have values
y1, which = f ( x1),

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:43.040
y2, which = f ( x2), all the way
up to yn, which = f ( xn).

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:46.190
And again, the spacing here
that we're talking

00:02:46.190 --> 00:02:50.690
about is b - a / n.

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:52.640
So remember that spacing,
that's going to be the

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:57.100
connection that we'll draw.

00:02:57.100 --> 00:03:08.440
Then the Riemann sum is y1
through yn, the sum of (y1 ...

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:12.080
yn) delta x.

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:15.680
And that's what tends, as delta
x goes to 0, to the

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:23.400
integral. .

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:27.300
The only change in point of view
if I want to write this

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:32.180
limiting property, which is
right above here, the only

00:03:32.180 --> 00:03:36.340
change between here and here
is that I want to divide by

00:03:36.340 --> 00:03:38.850
the length of the
interval. b - a.

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:42.000
So I will divide
by b - a here.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.230
And divide by b - a over here.

00:03:48.230 --> 00:03:53.510
And then I'll just check what
this thing actually is.

00:03:53.510 --> 00:03:57.560
Delta x / b - a, what
is that factor?

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:01.930
Well, if we look over here to
what delta x is, if you divide

00:04:01.930 --> 00:04:07.040
by b - a, it's 1 / n.

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:10.210
So the factor delta
x / b - a = 1 / n.

00:04:10.210 --> 00:04:15.210
That's what I put over here, the
sum of y1 through yn / n.

00:04:15.210 --> 00:04:18.860
And as this tends to
0, it's the same

00:04:18.860 --> 00:04:22.760
as n going to infinity.

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:25.610
Those are the same things.

00:04:25.610 --> 00:04:27.450
The average value and
the integral are

00:04:27.450 --> 00:04:28.460
very closely related.

00:04:28.460 --> 00:04:32.130
There's only this difference
that we're dividing by the

00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:36.440
length of the interval.

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:38.810
I want to give an example
which is an incredibly

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:41.800
simpleminded one, but it'll
come into play later on.

00:04:41.800 --> 00:04:47.040
So let's take the example
of a constant.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:50.730
And this is, I hope, will make
you slightly less confused

00:04:50.730 --> 00:04:52.540
about what I just wrote.

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:55.170
As well as making you think that
this is as simpleminded

00:04:55.170 --> 00:04:57.370
and reasonable as
it should be.

00:04:57.370 --> 00:05:00.310
If I check what the average
value of this constant is,

00:05:00.310 --> 00:05:04.680
it's given by this relatively
complicated formula here.

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:07.170
That is, I have to integrate
the function c.

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:09.570
Well, it's just the
constant c.

00:05:09.570 --> 00:05:12.320
And however you do this, as an
antiderivative I was thinking

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:14.560
of it as a rectangle, the answer
that you're going to

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:18.310
get is c here.

00:05:18.310 --> 00:05:19.490
So work that out.

00:05:19.490 --> 00:05:20.730
The answer is c.

00:05:20.730 --> 00:05:26.320
And so the fact that the average
of c = c, which had

00:05:26.320 --> 00:05:30.280
better be the case for averages,
explains the

00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:31.760
denominator.

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:36.690
Explains the 1 / b - a there.

00:05:36.690 --> 00:05:39.190
That's cooked up exactly so that
the average of a constant

00:05:39.190 --> 00:05:40.230
is what it's supposed to be.

00:05:40.230 --> 00:05:42.250
Otherwise we have the wrong
normalizing factor.

00:05:42.250 --> 00:05:45.450
We've clearly got a piece of
nonsense on our hands.

00:05:45.450 --> 00:05:51.580
And incidentally, it also
explains the 1 / n in the very

00:05:51.580 --> 00:05:53.460
first formula that
I wrote down.

00:05:53.460 --> 00:05:56.380
The reason why this is called
the average, or one reason why

00:05:56.380 --> 00:05:59.400
it's the right thing, is that if
you took the same constant

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:02.020
c, for y all the way across
there n times, if you divide

00:06:02.020 --> 00:06:03.930
it by n, you get back c.

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:05.770
That's what we mean by average
value and that's

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:11.370
why the n is there.

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:14.960
So that was an easy example.

00:06:14.960 --> 00:06:17.830
Now none of the examples that we
are going to give are going

00:06:17.830 --> 00:06:20.000
to be all that complicated.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.460
But they will get sort of
steadily more sophisticated.

00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:35.930
The second example is going to
be the average height of a

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:47.860
point on a semicircle.

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:52.800
And maybe I'll draw a picture of
the semicircle first here.

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:54.930
And we'll just make
it the standard

00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:58.840
circle, the unit circle.

00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:04.890
So maybe I should have called
it a unit semicircle.

00:07:04.890 --> 00:07:07.680
This is the point negative
1, this is the point 1.

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:12.690
And we're picking a point over
here and we're going to take

00:07:12.690 --> 00:07:17.210
