00:16:57.720 --> 00:16:59.090
these two equal lengths.

00:16:59.090 --> 00:17:01.320
But here, with respect to theta,
this is relatively

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:03.090
short and this is much larger.

00:17:03.090 --> 00:17:05.960
So, as I say, the theta
variable's emphasizing the

00:17:05.960 --> 00:17:09.140
lower parts of the
semicircle more.

00:17:09.140 --> 00:17:11.070
That's because this length
is shorter and

00:17:11.070 --> 00:17:12.340
this length is longer.

00:17:12.340 --> 00:17:16.130
Whereas these two
are the same.

00:17:16.130 --> 00:17:20.110
It's a balancing act of
the relative weights.

00:17:20.110 --> 00:17:22.290
I'm going to say that again
in a different way,

00:17:22.290 --> 00:17:25.320
and maybe this will.

00:17:25.320 --> 00:17:31.810
The lower part is more
important for theta.

00:17:31.810 --> 00:17:32.190
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:32.190 --> 00:17:33.930
PROFESSOR: So the question is,
but shouldn't it have a bigger

00:17:33.930 --> 00:17:35.920
value because it's
a longer length.

00:17:35.920 --> 00:17:37.620
Never with averages.

00:17:37.620 --> 00:17:39.540
Whatever the length is,
we're always dividing.

00:17:39.540 --> 00:17:42.760
We're always compensating
by the total.

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:45.410
We have the integral from 0 to
pi, but we're dividing by pi.

00:17:45.410 --> 00:17:48.060
Here we had the integral
from - 1 to 1, but

00:17:48.060 --> 00:17:49.760
we're dividing by 2.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:52.220
So we divide by something
different each time.

00:17:52.220 --> 00:17:53.850
And this is very,
very important.

00:17:53.850 --> 00:17:56.550
It's that the average of a
constant is that same constant

00:17:56.550 --> 00:17:58.070
regardless of which
one we did.

00:17:58.070 --> 00:18:00.930
So if it were a constant, we
would always compensate for

00:18:00.930 --> 00:18:01.270
the length.

00:18:01.270 --> 00:18:03.780
So the length never matters.

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:09.160
If it's the integral from 0 to
1,000,000, or 100, let's say,

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:12.330
1/100 cdx, it's just the same.

00:18:12.330 --> 00:18:14.160
It's always that, it doesn't
matter how long it is.

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:18.050
Because we compensate.

00:18:18.050 --> 00:18:19.730
That's really the difference
between an integral and an

00:18:19.730 --> 00:18:24.750
average, is that we're dividing
by the total.

00:18:24.750 --> 00:18:27.560
Now I want to introduce another
notion, which is

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:31.500
actually what's underlying these
two examples that I just

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:32.060
wrote down.

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:36.050
And this is by far the one which
you should emphasize the

00:18:36.050 --> 00:18:39.470
most in your thoughts.

00:18:39.470 --> 00:18:45.590
Because it is much more
flexible, and is much more

00:18:45.590 --> 00:18:50.770
typical of real life problems.
So the idea of a weighted

00:18:50.770 --> 00:18:53.920
average is the following.

00:18:53.920 --> 00:18:57.580
You take the integral, say from
a to b, of some function.

00:18:57.580 --> 00:19:02.550
But now you multiply
by a weight.

00:19:02.550 --> 00:19:05.560
And you have to divide
by the total.

00:19:05.560 --> 00:19:07.410
And what's the total
going to be?

00:19:07.410 --> 00:19:11.820
It's the integral from a to b
of this total weighting that

00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:17.190
we have. Now, why is this
the correct notion?

00:19:17.190 --> 00:19:20.420
I'm going to explain it
to you in two ways.

00:19:20.420 --> 00:19:24.990
The first is this very
simpleminded thing that I

00:19:24.990 --> 00:19:30.480
wrote on the board there,
with the constants.

00:19:30.480 --> 00:19:38.480
What we want is the average
value of c to be c.

00:19:38.480 --> 00:19:40.820
Otherwise this makes no
sense as an average.

00:19:40.820 --> 00:19:43.070
Now, let's just look at
this definition here.

00:19:43.070 --> 00:19:44.660
And see that that's correct.

00:19:44.660 --> 00:19:50.900
If you integrate c, from a to
b, w ( x) dx, and you divide

00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:56.030
by the integral from a to b, w (
x) dx, not surprisingly, the

00:19:56.030 --> 00:19:57.020
c factors out.

00:19:57.020 --> 00:19:59.010
It's a constant.

00:19:59.010 --> 00:20:03.430
So this is c times the integral
a to b, w (x), dx,

00:20:03.430 --> 00:20:05.380
divided by the same thing.

00:20:05.380 --> 00:20:08.390
And that's why we picked it.

00:20:08.390 --> 00:20:10.170
We picked it so that these
things would cancel.

00:20:10.170 --> 00:20:14.660
And this would give c.

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:17.910
So in the previous case, this
property explains the

00:20:17.910 --> 00:20:20.140
denominator.

00:20:20.140 --> 00:20:29.760
And again over here, it explains
the denominator.

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:32.510
And let me just give you
one more explanation.

00:20:32.510 --> 00:20:38.340
Which is maybe a real life
pretend real life example.

00:20:38.340 --> 00:20:43.060
You have a stock which you
bought for $10 one year.

00:20:43.060 --> 00:20:46.740
And then six months later you
brought some more for $20.

00:20:46.740 --> 00:20:50.360
And then you bought
some more for $30.

00:20:50.360 --> 00:20:53.810
Now, what's the average
price of your stock?

00:20:53.810 --> 00:20:58.370
Well, it depends on how many
shares you bought.

00:20:58.370 --> 00:21:01.290
If you bought this many shares
the first time, and this many

00:21:01.290 --> 00:21:03.760
shares the second time, and
this many shares the third

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:07.230
time, this is the total
amount that you spent.

00:21:07.230 --> 00:21:14.090
And the average price is the
total price divided by the

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:17.120
total number of shares.

00:21:17.120 --> 00:21:22.560
And this is the discrete analog
of this continuous

00:21:22.560 --> 00:21:24.070
averaging process here.

00:21:24.070 --> 00:21:28.260
The function f now, so I use w
for weight, the function f now

00:21:28.260 --> 00:21:31.150
is the function whose values
are 10, 20 and 30.

00:21:31.150 --> 00:21:35.800
And the weightings are the
relative importance of the

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:42.030
different purchases.

00:21:42.030 --> 00:21:51.600
So again, these wi's
are weights.

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:52.710
There was another question.

00:21:52.710 --> 00:21:54.400
Out in the audience,
at some point.

00:21:54.400 --> 00:21:55.300
Over here, yes.

00:21:55.300 --> 00:22:04.520
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:06.920
PROFESSOR: Very, very
good point.

00:22:06.920 --> 00:22:15.710
So in this numerator here, the
statement is, in this example,

00:22:15.710 --> 00:22:17.020
we factored out c.

00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:20.710
But here we cannot factor
out f ( x).

00:22:20.710 --> 00:22:23.450
That's extremely important and
that is the whole point.

00:22:23.450 --> 00:22:25.950
So, in other words, the weighted
average is very

00:22:25.950 --> 00:22:29.820
interesting you have to do two
different integrals to figure

00:22:29.820 --> 00:22:32.380
it out in general.

00:22:32.380 --> 00:22:34.120
When it happens that
this is c, it's an

00:22:34.120 --> 00:22:35.430
extremely boring integral.

00:22:35.430 --> 00:22:37.620
Which in fact because, it's an
average, you don't even have

00:22:37.620 --> 00:22:38.930
to calculate at all.

00:22:38.930 --> 00:22:41.490
Factor it out and cancel these
things and never bother to

00:22:41.490 --> 00:22:43.530
calculate these two numbers.

00:22:43.530 --> 00:22:46.580
So these massive numbers
just cancel.

00:22:46.580 --> 00:22:48.975
So it's a very special property
of a constant, that

00:22:48.975 --> 00:22:55.650
it factors out.

00:22:55.650 --> 00:23:00.100
That was our first discussion,
and now with this example I'm

00:23:00.100 --> 00:23:02.900
going to go back to the heating
up of the witches'

00:23:02.900 --> 00:23:07.600
cauldron and we'll use average
value to illustrate the

00:23:07.600 --> 00:23:19.700
integral that we get in
that context as well.

00:23:19.700 --> 00:23:20.910
I remind you, let's see.

00:23:20.910 --> 00:23:25.480
The situation with the witches'
cauldron was this.

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:40.260
The first important thing is
that there were, so this is

00:23:40.260 --> 00:23:42.770
the big cauldron here.

00:23:42.770 --> 00:23:47.210
This is the one whose height
is 1 meter and

00:23:47.210 --> 00:23:53.190
whose width is 2 meters.

00:23:53.190 --> 00:23:56.540
And it's a parabola of
revolution here.

00:23:56.540 --> 00:24:06.500
And it had about approximately
1600 liters in it.

00:24:06.500 --> 00:24:14.640
And this curve was y = x^2.

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:18.560
And the situation that I
described at the end of last

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:25.210
time was that the initial
temperature was

00:24:25.210 --> 00:24:28.560
T = 0 degrees Celsius.

00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:35.320
And the final temperature,
instead of being a constant

00:24:35.320 --> 00:24:41.290
temperature, we were heating
this guy up from the bottom.

00:24:41.290 --> 00:24:48.340
And it was hotter on the
bottom than on the top.

00:24:48.340 --> 00:24:54.870
And the final temperature was
given by the formula T = 100 -

00:24:54.870 --> 00:24:57.880
30 times the height y.

00:24:57.880 --> 00:25:04.090
So at y = 0, at the
bottom, it's 100.

00:25:04.090 --> 00:25:10.730
And at the top, T
= 70 degrees.

00:25:10.730 --> 00:25:15.420
OK, so this is the final
configuration for the

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:16.020
temperature.

00:25:16.020 --> 00:25:33.100
And the question was how
much energy do we need.

00:25:33.100 --> 00:25:36.670
So, the first observation here,
and this is the reason

00:25:36.670 --> 00:25:42.630
for giving this example, is that
it's important to realize

00:25:42.630 --> 00:25:54.700
that you want to use the method
of disks in this case.

00:25:54.700 --> 00:25:58.040
The reason, so it doesn't have
to do with, you shouldn't

00:25:58.040 --> 00:26:02.060
think of the disks first. But
what you should think of is

00:26:02.060 --> 00:26:05.010
the horizontal.

00:26:05.010 --> 00:26:09.780
We must use horizontals because
T is constant on

00:26:09.780 --> 00:26:10.840
horizontals.

00:26:10.840 --> 00:26:12.740
It's not constant
on verticals.

00:26:12.740 --> 00:26:16.130
If we set things up with shells,
as we did last time,

00:26:16.130 --> 00:26:18.980
to compute the volume
of this, then T will

00:26:18.980 --> 00:26:21.760
vary along the shell.

00:26:21.760 --> 00:26:24.620
And we will still have an
averaging problem, an integral

00:26:24.620 --> 00:26:26.730
problem along the vertical
portion.

00:26:26.730 --> 00:26:29.460
But if we do it this way,
T is constant on

00:26:29.460 --> 00:26:31.770
this whole level here.

00:26:31.770 --> 00:26:34.400
And so there's no more
calculus involved in

00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:36.140
calculating what the
contribution is

00:26:36.140 --> 00:26:39.840
of any given level.

00:26:39.840 --> 00:26:49.620
So t is constant
on horizontals.

00:26:49.620 --> 00:26:52.750
Actually, in disguise, this
is that same trick

00:26:52.750 --> 00:26:53.370
that we have here.

00:26:53.370 --> 00:26:55.680
We can factor constants
out of integrals.

00:26:55.680 --> 00:26:57.580
You could view it as an
integral, but the point is

00:26:57.580 --> 00:27:03.480
that it's more elementary
than that.

00:27:03.480 --> 00:27:06.430
Now I have to set
it up for you.

00:27:06.430 --> 00:27:09.230
And in order to do that, I
need to remember what the

00:27:09.230 --> 00:27:10.470
equation is.

00:27:10.470 --> 00:27:12.960
Which is y = x ^2.

00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:19.030
And the formula for the total
amount of energy is going to

00:27:19.030 --> 00:27:25.000
be volume times the
number of degrees.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:31.480
That's going to be equal to the
energy that we need here.

00:27:31.480 --> 00:27:33.250
And so let's add it up.

00:27:33.250 --> 00:27:38.540
It's the integral from 0 to 1,
and this is with respect to y.

00:27:38.540 --> 00:27:41.300
So the y level goes
from 0 to 1.

00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:47.310
This top level's y = 1, this
bottom level's y = 0.

00:27:47.310 --> 00:27:55.260
And the disk that we get, this
is the point (x, y) here, is

00:27:55.260 --> 00:27:56.220
rotated around.

00:27:56.220 --> 00:28:01.230
And its radius is x.

00:28:01.230 --> 00:28:05.500
So the thickness is dy,
and the area of

00:28:05.500 --> 00:28:09.480
the disk is pi x^2.

00:28:09.480 --> 00:28:13.830
And the thing that we're
averaging is T. Well, we're

00:28:13.830 --> 00:28:16.010
not yet averaging, we're
just integrating it.

00:28:16.010 --> 00:28:24.170
We're just adding
up the total.

00:28:24.170 --> 00:28:29.080
Now I'm just going to plug in
the various values for this.

00:28:29.080 --> 00:28:36.580
And what I'm going to get is
T, again, = 100 - 30y.

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:40.960
And this radius is measured
up to this very end.

00:28:40.960 --> 00:28:42.440
So x^2 = y.

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:45.410
So this is pi y dy.

00:28:45.410 --> 00:28:47.800
And this is the integral that
we'll be able to evaluate.

00:28:47.800 --> 00:28:48.660
Yeah, question.

00:28:48.660 --> 00:28:50.250
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:50.250 --> 00:29:00.070
PROFESSOR: All right.

00:29:00.070 --> 00:29:05.710
Well, let's carry this out.

00:29:05.710 --> 00:29:09.160
Let's finish off the
calculation here.

00:29:09.160 --> 00:29:10.230
Let's see.

00:29:10.230 --> 00:29:16.380
This is equal to, what
does it equal to.

00:29:16.380 --> 00:29:19.580
Well, I'll put it over here.

00:29:19.580 --> 00:29:27.780
It's equal to 50 pi y ^2 -
right, because this is 100 pi

00:29:27.780 --> 00:29:36.950
y, and then there's a 30, this
is 100 pi y - 30 pi y ^2, and

00:29:36.950 --> 00:29:38.780
I have to take the
antiderivative of that.

00:29:38.780 --> 00:29:45.450
So I get 50 pi y ^2, and
I get 10 pi y ^3.

00:29:45.450 --> 00:29:48.120
Evaluate it at 0 and 1.

00:29:48.120 --> 00:29:57.930
And that is 40 pi.

00:29:57.930 --> 00:30:05.140
Now, I spent a tremendous
amount of time last time

00:30:05.140 --> 00:30:07.900
focusing on units.

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:10.710
Because I want to tell you
how to get a realistic

00:30:10.710 --> 00:30:12.080
number out of this.

00:30:12.080 --> 00:30:16.515
And there's a subtle point here
that I pointed out last

00:30:16.515 --> 00:30:18.650
time that had to do with
changing meters to

00:30:18.650 --> 00:30:19.160
centimeters.

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:22.570
I claim that I've treated
